    var galleryObjects = {"resource_2290":{"resource_link":"..\/2290","resource_url":"http:\/\/www.artic.edu\/aic\/collections\/citi\/resources\/Rsrc_002290.jpg","resource_title":"01. Calumet New Town, Calumet, IN. \"Air View of the Town\" rendering, brochure, p.6, [1949].","resource_description":"1948-1949.<br \/>\n<br \/>\nThe Calumet New Town plan, sponsored by General American Transportation Corporation CEO, Lester Selig, was conceived with the intent of creating a new, company town\u2014in the spirit of Pullman, but \"renewed\"\u2014from scratch. Selig's unorthodox plan was to retain ownership of the workingmen's houses by the company, yet with the explicit promise of a new home every worker, every 25 years.<br \/>\n<br \/>\nIn this aerial plan of the town, the separation of zones by function\u2014a hallmark of the planner Ludwig Hilberseimer, with whom Goldberg studied at the Bauhaus\u2014is readily apparent. Hilberseimer's influence is also clear in the communities of residential \"superblocks,\" buffered on two sides by open land. But rather than adopting Hilberseimer's process of \"community formation through living patterns caused by sun, wind, or traffic,\" Goldberg sought out Le Corbisier's model of \"community formation through humanism.\" The result was a plan that was to dramatically reduce the cost of living, including both food and transportation costs. More importantly, it intended to make a promise to workers that they \"would not be faced with a constantly degenerating pattern of living.\"<br \/>\n<br \/>\nUnfortunately, insurance companies became afraid that such an large grouping of houses in a tightly-knit community could become the \"tool of a rent strike in the event [the worker's] labor relations were unhappy\" and declined to support the project, effectively killing it\u2014though perhaps for good. Goldberg, in a later assessment of such \"monolithic living\" plans, found them less viable and attractive \"for the later twentieth-century American life.\"","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_002290.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"41.3916015625","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Architecture for Urbanism: Selections from the Bertrand Goldberg Archive,\" Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, November 1, 2011\u2013January 2, 2012<br \/>\n<br \/>\n<a href=&quot;http:\/\/digital-libraries.saic.edu\/u?\/mqc,14869&quot;>Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record<\/a>","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"architecture, city planning, housing"},"resource_2291":{"resource_link":"..\/2291","resource_url":"http:\/\/www.artic.edu\/aic\/collections\/citi\/resources\/Rsrc_002291.jpg","resource_title":"02. Untitled manuscript outline, n.d.","resource_description":"This undated outline traces the rationale behind Goldberg's \"city within a city\" philosophy.","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_002291.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"82.2763671875","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Architecture for Urbanism: Selections from the Bertrand Goldberg Archive,\" Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, November 1, 2011\u2013January 2, 2012<br \/>\n<br \/>\n<a href=&quot;http:\/\/digital-libraries.saic.edu\/u?\/mqc,14856&quot;>Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record<\/a>","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"architecture, city planning, housing"},"resource_2292":{"resource_link":"..\/2292","