 and commercial project planned for a waterfront area two miles south of Boston. Like Goldberg's early plan for River City, this sprawling development would have included high rises, light industry, shopping and office buildings, and cultural facilities.","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_002293.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"31.9599609375","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Architecture for Urbanism: Selections from the Bertrand Goldberg Archive,\" Case 8, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, November 1, 2011\u2013January 2, 2012<br \/>\n<br \/>\n<a href=&quot;http:\/\/digital-libraries.saic.edu\/u?\/mqc,14860&quot;>Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record<\/a>","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"architecture, housing"},"resource_2294":{"resource_link":"..\/2294","resource_url":"http:\/\/www.artic.edu\/aic\/collections\/citi\/resources\/Rsrc_002294.jpg","resource_title":"05. Burns-Jackson Project, Dayton, OH. \"Proposed Burns Jackson\" plan, n.d.","resource_description":"1966-1970.<br \/>\n<br \/>\nGoldberg's proposal to reinvent Burns-Jackson\u2014a neglected, but historic-ally rich neighborhood adjacent to Dayton's commercial center\u2014was not aimed at \"preserving the pastness of the past, but giving the past a future.\"* Because many existing buildings were not worthy of preservation, Goldberg's plan included new high-density residential towers, low-rise apartments and community buildings, as well as the restoration and rearrangement of historical homes. For reasons unknown, the city rejected Goldberg's \"community within a community\" plan, and it was never implemented.<br \/>\n<br \/>\n-------------------------------------------------------